<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,697,1889]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Diagnosis: 
<taxonomicName box="[447,606,737,762]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[447,606,737,762]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Pygommatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinctive by the following characters. Uniformly thick, pencil­like bristles of the face [absent in 
<taxonomicName authority="Martin" authorityName="Martin" box="[800,1001,777,803]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albatus">
<emphasis box="[800,886,777,802]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">albatus</emphasis>
(Martin)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Oldroyd" authorityName="Oldroyd" box="[1074,1311,777,803]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epicalus">
<emphasis box="[1074,1172,777,802]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">epicalus</emphasis>
(Oldroyd)
</taxonomicName>
]; absence of an anepimeral bristle; usually stout, erect bristles on one to four sternites [absent in 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarbrough and Marascia" authorityName="Scarbrough and Marascia" box="[398,805,857,883]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lulua">
<emphasis box="[398,459,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">lulua</emphasis>
(Scarbrough and Marascia)
</taxonomicName>
, wavy setae in 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarbrough and Marascia" authorityName="Scarbrough and Marascia" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comosus">
<emphasis box="[1008,1108,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">comosus</emphasis>
(Scarbrough and Marascia)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarbrough and Marascia" authorityName="Scarbrough and Marascia" box="[396,832,897,923]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imaginus">
<emphasis box="[396,503,897,922]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">imaginus</emphasis>
(Scarbrough and Marascia)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarbrough and Marascia" authorityName="Scarbrough and Marascia" box="[843,1268,897,923]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="renudus">
<emphasis box="[843,936,897,922]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">renudus</emphasis>
(Scarbrough and Marascia)
</taxonomicName>
]; the three digitate branches of the epandrium; reduced, often minute, gonostylus (
<figureCitation box="[1196,1314,937,963]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1572,1596]" captionTargetBox="[289,1292,456,1527]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[267,1321,449,1546]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Pygommatius apoticius Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 1 – 3. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 4. Hypandrial bristle with bracts; 5. Epandrium with three branches, dorsal view; 6. Gonostylus, lateral view; 7. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 8 – 9. Dorsal and ventral views; 10. Spermatheca; 11. Genital fork. Abbrevations: Ae = aedeagus; AS = aedeagal sheath; Ce = cercus; E p = epandrium; Ej = ejaculatory apodeme; DB = dorsal branch of epandrium; MB = middle branch of epandrium; VB = ventral branch of epandrium; DA = dorsal and VA = ventral apodemes of aedeagal sheath; Gc = gonocoxite; Gs = gonostylus; Hp = hypandrium; T = moundlike tubercle; St 8 = sternite 8; T 8 = tergite 8; T 9 = tergite 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170083/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs. 2, 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[264,338,977,1003]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 20" captionStartId="11.[264,383,1755,1779]" captionTargetBox="[295,1288,501,1697]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[281,1305,449,1729]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 20. Pygommatius iriga Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 12 – 14. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 15. Gonostylus, lateral view; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 17 – 18. Dorsal and ventral views; 19. Spermatheca; 20. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170084/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<number box="[264,293,977,1003]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="12.0">12</number>
–13
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[352,427,977,1003]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 29" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1276,515,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 29. Pygommatius misamis Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 21 – 23. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 24. Gonostylus, lateral view; 25. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 26 – 27. Dorsal and ventral views; 28. Spermatheca; 29. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170085/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">21–22</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[441,515,977,1003]" captionStart="FIGURES 30 – 38" captionStartId="17.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[311,1279,547,1694]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 30 – 38. Pygommatius montanus Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 30 – 32. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 33. Gonostylus, lateral view; 34. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 35 – 36. Dorsal and ventral views; 37. Spermatheca; 38. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170086/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
30– 
<number box="[483,515,977,1003]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="31.0">31</number>
</figureCitation>
); and a pair of prominent dorsal and ventral apodemes (
<figureCitation box="[1187,1271,977,1003]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1572,1596]" captionTargetBox="[289,1292,456,1527]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[267,1321,449,1546]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Pygommatius apoticius Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 1 – 3. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 4. Hypandrial bristle with bracts; 5. Epandrium with three branches, dorsal view; 6. Gonostylus, lateral view; 7. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 8 – 9. Dorsal and ventral views; 10. Spermatheca; 11. Genital fork. Abbrevations: Ae = aedeagus; AS = aedeagal sheath; Ce = cercus; E p = epandrium; Ej = ejaculatory apodeme; DB = dorsal branch of epandrium; MB = middle branch of epandrium; VB = ventral branch of epandrium; DA = dorsal and VA = ventral apodemes of aedeagal sheath; Gc = gonocoxite; Gs = gonostylus; Hp = hypandrium; T = moundlike tubercle; St 8 = sternite 8; T 8 = tergite 8; T 9 = tergite 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170083/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs. 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1286,1318,977,1003]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 20" captionStartId="11.[264,383,1755,1779]" captionTargetBox="[295,1288,501,1697]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[281,1305,449,1729]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 20. Pygommatius iriga Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 12 – 14. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 15. Gonostylus, lateral view; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 17 – 18. Dorsal and ventral views; 19. Spermatheca; 20. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170084/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">16</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[264,296,1017,1043]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 29" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1276,515,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 29. Pygommatius misamis Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 21 – 23. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 24. Gonostylus, lateral view; 25. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 26 – 27. Dorsal and ventral views; 28. Spermatheca; 29. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170085/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[311,342,1017,1043]" captionStart="FIGURES 30 – 38" captionStartId="17.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[311,1279,547,1694]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 30 – 38. Pygommatius montanus Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 30 – 32. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 33. Gonostylus, lateral view; 34. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 35 – 36. Dorsal and ventral views; 37. Spermatheca; 38. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170086/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">34</figureCitation>
) originating from the posterior margin of the aedeagal sheath easily separate the genus from 
<taxonomicName box="[412,533,1057,1082]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[412,533,1057,1082]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Ommatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The second and third branches of the epandrium are prominent whereas the first one is quite short, extending only to the base of the ventral lamella; these combined features are absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[682,803,1137,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[682,803,1137,1162]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Ommatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The short, inflated aedeagal sheath and elongated ejaculatory apodeme are distinctive (
<figureCitation box="[849,938,1177,1203]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1572,1596]" captionTargetBox="[289,1292,456,1527]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[267,1321,449,1546]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Pygommatius apoticius Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 1 – 3. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 4. Hypandrial bristle with bracts; 5. Epandrium with three branches, dorsal view; 6. Gonostylus, lateral view; 7. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 8 – 9. Dorsal and ventral views; 10. Spermatheca; 11. Genital fork. Abbrevations: Ae = aedeagus; AS = aedeagal sheath; Ce = cercus; E p = epandrium; Ej = ejaculatory apodeme; DB = dorsal branch of epandrium; MB = middle branch of epandrium; VB = ventral branch of epandrium; DA = dorsal and VA = ventral apodemes of aedeagal sheath; Gc = gonocoxite; Gs = gonostylus; Hp = hypandrium; T = moundlike tubercle; St 8 = sternite 8; T 8 = tergite 8; T 9 = tergite 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170083/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs. 7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[958,990,1177,1203]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 20" captionStartId="11.[264,383,1755,1779]" captionTargetBox="[295,1288,501,1697]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[281,1305,449,1729]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 20. Pygommatius iriga Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 12 – 14. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 15. Gonostylus, lateral view; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 17 – 18. Dorsal and ventral views; 19. Spermatheca; 20. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170084/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">16</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1009,1041,1177,1203]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 29" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1276,515,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 29. Pygommatius misamis Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 21 – 23. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 24. Gonostylus, lateral view; 25. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 26 – 27. Dorsal and ventral views; 28. Spermatheca; 29. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170085/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1059,1092,1177,1203]" captionStart="FIGURES 30 – 38" captionStartId="17.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[311,1279,547,1694]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 30 – 38. Pygommatius montanus Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 30 – 32. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 33. Gonostylus, lateral view; 34. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 35 – 36. Dorsal and ventral views; 37. Spermatheca; 38. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170086/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">34</figureCitation>
). Additionally, the hypandrium (
<figureCitation box="[424,572,1217,1243]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1572,1596]" captionTargetBox="[289,1292,456,1527]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[267,1321,449,1546]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Pygommatius apoticius Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 1 – 3. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 4. Hypandrial bristle with bracts; 5. Epandrium with three branches, dorsal view; 6. Gonostylus, lateral view; 7. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 8 – 9. Dorsal and ventral views; 10. Spermatheca; 11. Genital fork. Abbrevations: Ae = aedeagus; AS = aedeagal sheath; Ce = cercus; E p = epandrium; Ej = ejaculatory apodeme; DB = dorsal branch of epandrium; MB = middle branch of epandrium; VB = ventral branch of epandrium; DA = dorsal and VA = ventral apodemes of aedeagal sheath; Gc = gonocoxite; Gs = gonostylus; Hp = hypandrium; T = moundlike tubercle; St 8 = sternite 8; T 8 = tergite 8; T 9 = tergite 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170083/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs. 1, 3, 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[587,665,1217,1243]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 20" captionStartId="11.[264,383,1755,1779]" captionTargetBox="[295,1288,501,1697]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[281,1305,449,1729]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 20. Pygommatius iriga Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 12 – 14. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 15. Gonostylus, lateral view; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 17 – 18. Dorsal and ventral views; 19. Spermatheca; 20. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170084/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">12, 14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[680,758,1217,1243]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 29" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1276,515,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 29. Pygommatius misamis Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 21 – 23. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 24. Gonostylus, lateral view; 25. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 26 – 27. Dorsal and ventral views; 28. Spermatheca; 29. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170085/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">21, 23</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[772,849,1217,1243]" captionStart="FIGURES 30 – 38" captionStartId="17.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[311,1279,547,1694]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 30 – 38. Pygommatius montanus Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 30 – 32. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 33. Gonostylus, lateral view; 34. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 35 – 36. Dorsal and ventral views; 37. Spermatheca; 38. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170086/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
30, 
<number box="[819,849,1217,1243]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="33.0">33</number>
</figureCitation>
) is usually slightly to strongly inflated, bearing a transverse or broader cluster of long bristles, that are straight, curved, or wavy, except within the Afrotropical 
<taxonomicName box="[625,725,1297,1322]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comosus">
<emphasis box="[625,725,1297,1322]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">comosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. The bristles are often flat and wide, fused basally, sometimes bearing short seta­like bracts dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[1045,1132,1337,1363]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1572,1596]" captionTargetBox="[289,1292,456,1527]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[267,1321,449,1546]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Pygommatius apoticius Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 1 – 3. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 4. Hypandrial bristle with bracts; 5. Epandrium with three branches, dorsal view; 6. Gonostylus, lateral view; 7. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 8 – 9. Dorsal and ventral views; 10. Spermatheca; 11. Genital fork. Abbrevations: Ae = aedeagus; AS = aedeagal sheath; Ce = cercus; E p = epandrium; Ej = ejaculatory apodeme; DB = dorsal branch of epandrium; MB = middle branch of epandrium; VB = ventral branch of epandrium; DA = dorsal and VA = ventral apodemes of aedeagal sheath; Gc = gonocoxite; Gs = gonostylus; Hp = hypandrium; T = moundlike tubercle; St 8 = sternite 8; T 8 = tergite 8; T 9 = tergite 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170083/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1148,1179,1337,1363]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 20" captionStartId="11.[264,383,1755,1779]" captionTargetBox="[295,1288,501,1697]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[281,1305,449,1729]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 20. Pygommatius iriga Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 12 – 14. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 15. Gonostylus, lateral view; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 17 – 18. Dorsal and ventral views; 19. Spermatheca; 20. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170084/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">12</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1195,1227,1337,1363]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 29" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1276,515,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 29. Pygommatius misamis Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 21 – 23. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 24. Gonostylus, lateral view; 25. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 26 – 27. Dorsal and ventral views; 28. Spermatheca; 29. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170085/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<number box="[1195,1227,1337,1363]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
), or are unusually thick apically (see 
<taxonomicName box="[606,716,1377,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="daknistus">
<emphasis box="[606,716,1377,1402]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">daknistus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Fig. 
<number box="[785,831,1377,1403]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="119.0">119</number>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Oldroyd" box="[843,1010,1377,1403]" pageId="2" pageNumber="22" refString="Oldroyd, H. (1972) Robber flies (Diptera: Asilidae) of the Philippine Islands. Pacific Insects, 14, 201 - 337." type="journal article" year="1972">
Oldroyd 
<number box="[947,1010,1377,1403]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1972.0">1972</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,697,1889]" lastBlockId="3.[264,1324,284,1470]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis box="[312,372,1417,1442]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Body</emphasis>
: Usually slender, sometimes short. 
<emphasis box="[791,864,1417,1442]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Head:</emphasis>
Lower face of male with contrastingly thick, pencil­like bristles, tapering only slightly from base to apex, often extend to or near apex of proboscis; setae sparse. Flagellum short, slightly longer than scape or pedicel. Palpus and proboscis black, narrow base usually pale. Occipital bristles thin, strongly proclinate. 
<emphasis box="[402,487,1577,1602]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Thorax</emphasis>
: Mesonotum black, sometimes subshiny, postalar callus often pale; tomentum usually thin. Scutellum with two marginal scutellar bristles; preapical groove absent. Pleuron entirely to mostly dark, or anepisternum and katapisternum mostly and meron partly blackish, otherwise pale; anepimeral bristle absent, sometimes long, thin setae present. 
<emphasis box="[450,508,1737,1762]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Wing</emphasis>
: Hyaline; apical 
<number box="[743,754,1737,1763]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[766,781,1737,1763]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="3.0">3</number>
to 
<number box="[839,849,1737,1763]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[861,877,1737,1763]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2.0">2</number>
and posterior 
<number box="[1077,1092,1737,1763]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number box="[1101,1114,1737,1763]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="3.0">3</number>
narrowly dense microtrichose; rarely entirely dense microtrichose. Cell R 
<number box="[971,979,1793,1807]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="4.0">4</number>
short, base narrow, beyond apex of cell d, sides gradually wider to wing margin. Cell m 
<number box="[1013,1021,1836,1850]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
narrow basally, vein M 
<number box="[1314,1322,1836,1850]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
moderately to strongly arched basally. 
<emphasis box="[737,781,1864,1889]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Leg</emphasis>
: Femora usually with setae or weak bristles ventrally, bristles when present often unusually long and wide spaced; fore and middle femur sometimes with row of stout bristles ventrally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,284,1470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis box="[312,422,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Abdominal sternites 
<number box="[691,734,364,390]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5</number>
of male usually, sometimes 
<number box="[1084,1099,364,390]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
and 
<number box="[1163,1179,364,390]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="6.0">6</number>
, with stout, erect bristles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,284,1470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis box="[312,502,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Male terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[519,631,444,470]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1572,1596]" captionTargetBox="[289,1292,456,1527]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[267,1321,449,1546]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Pygommatius apoticius Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 1 – 3. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 4. Hypandrial bristle with bracts; 5. Epandrium with three branches, dorsal view; 6. Gonostylus, lateral view; 7. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 8 – 9. Dorsal and ventral views; 10. Spermatheca; 11. Genital fork. Abbrevations: Ae = aedeagus; AS = aedeagal sheath; Ce = cercus; E p = epandrium; Ej = ejaculatory apodeme; DB = dorsal branch of epandrium; MB = middle branch of epandrium; VB = ventral branch of epandrium; DA = dorsal and VA = ventral apodemes of aedeagal sheath; Gc = gonocoxite; Gs = gonostylus; Hp = hypandrium; T = moundlike tubercle; St 8 = sternite 8; T 8 = tergite 8; T 9 = tergite 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170083/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs. 
<number box="[586,600,444,470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
–7
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[644,718,444,470]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 20" captionStartId="11.[264,383,1755,1779]" captionTargetBox="[295,1288,501,1697]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[281,1305,449,1729]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 20. Pygommatius iriga Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 12 – 14. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 15. Gonostylus, lateral view; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 17 – 18. Dorsal and ventral views; 19. Spermatheca; 20. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170084/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">12–16</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[732,806,444,470]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 29" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1276,515,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 29. Pygommatius misamis Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 21 – 23. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 24. Gonostylus, lateral view; 25. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 26 – 27. Dorsal and ventral views; 28. Spermatheca; 29. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170085/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">21–25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[819,896,444,470]" captionStart="FIGURES 30 – 38" captionStartId="17.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[311,1279,547,1694]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 30 – 38. Pygommatius montanus Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 30 – 32. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 33. Gonostylus, lateral view; 34. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 35 – 36. Dorsal and ventral views; 37. Spermatheca; 38. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170086/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
30– 
<number box="[862,896,444,470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="34.0">34</number>
</figureCitation>
): Cercus long, three to five times as long as wide. Epandrium digitate, with three branches, each separated by deep lobe or sinus; dorsal branch short, usually extending to or just beyond base of proctiger; median and ventral branches much longer and prominent. Gonostylus reduced, often minute. Aedeagus usually narrow apically, slightly to strongly sigmoid, aedeagal sheath slightly to strongly inflated dorsally, sometimes forming diagnostic features; pair of dorsal and ventral aedeagal apodemes present; ejaculatory apodeme long, three or four times as long as aedeagus+sheath. Hypandrium slightly or strongly produced, usually with a transverse stripe or broader cluster of bristles, the latter straight, curved or wavy; bristles often flat apically, fused or/and with short bracts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,284,1470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis box="[312,529,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Female terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[544,668,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="6.[264,382,1572,1596]" captionTargetBox="[289,1292,456,1527]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[267,1321,449,1546]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Pygommatius apoticius Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 1 – 3. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 4. Hypandrial bristle with bracts; 5. Epandrium with three branches, dorsal view; 6. Gonostylus, lateral view; 7. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 8 – 9. Dorsal and ventral views; 10. Spermatheca; 11. Genital fork. Abbrevations: Ae = aedeagus; AS = aedeagal sheath; Ce = cercus; E p = epandrium; Ej = ejaculatory apodeme; DB = dorsal branch of epandrium; MB = middle branch of epandrium; VB = ventral branch of epandrium; DA = dorsal and VA = ventral apodemes of aedeagal sheath; Gc = gonocoxite; Gs = gonostylus; Hp = hypandrium; T = moundlike tubercle; St 8 = sternite 8; T 8 = tergite 8; T 9 = tergite 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170083/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs. 
<number box="[611,625,844,870]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="8.0">8</number>
–11
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[681,756,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 20" captionStartId="11.[264,383,1755,1779]" captionTargetBox="[295,1288,501,1697]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[281,1305,449,1729]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 20. Pygommatius iriga Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 12 – 14. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 15. Gonostylus, lateral view; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female, 17 – 18. Dorsal and ventral views; 19. Spermatheca; 20. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170084/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">17–20</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[767,842,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 29" captionStartId="14.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1276,515,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 29. Pygommatius misamis Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 21 – 23. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 24. Gonostylus, lateral view; 25. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 26 – 27. Dorsal and ventral views; 28. Spermatheca; 29. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170085/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">26–29</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[853,929,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURES 30 – 38" captionStartId="17.[264,383,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[311,1279,547,1694]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1305,489,1722]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 30 – 38. Pygommatius montanus Scarbrough, terminalia. Male, 30 – 32. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 33. Gonostylus, lateral view; 34. Aedeagus lateral view. Female, 35 – 36. Dorsal and ventral views; 37. Spermatheca; 38. Genital fork." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170086/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
35– 
<number box="[896,929,844,870]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="38.0">38</number>
</figureCitation>
): Sternite 
<number box="[1049,1064,844,870]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="8.0">8</number>
simple, apical margin slightly to strongly pointed medially, often slightly emarginated or lobed. Genital fork Yshaped, consisting of two thin lateral sclerities and connected medially by sclerotized, sometimes membranous, basal sclerite. Spermatheca obpyriform, slightly to strongly sigmoid, slightly sclerotized, without apparent surface characters; apical spermathecal duct thin, membranous, inserted anteapically, 
<number box="[802,813,1044,1070]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[824,839,1044,1070]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="3.0">3</number>
to as long as spermatheca; common duct very short.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,284,1470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Remarks. 
<taxonomicName box="[432,591,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Pygommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[432,591,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Pygommatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes black to yellow species similar in shape and size to 
<taxonomicName box="[264,384,1164,1189]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,384,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ommatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs by the characters in the diagnosis above. Additionally, it differs from 
<emphasis box="[264,423,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Metommatius</emphasis>
by the double row of setae below the style, wholly tomentose mesonotum, presence of scutellar bristles, sparse bristles below the hind femur, absence of anepimeral bristles, and characters of the terminalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,284,1470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Distribution. Sub­Saharan Africa, 
<collectingCountry box="[749,893,1324,1350]" name="Madagascar" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[915,979,1324,1350]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1002,1112,1324,1350]" name="Malaysia" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, western 
<collectingCountry box="[1245,1318,1324,1350]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[264,381,1364,1390]" name="Indonesia" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[393,529,1364,1390]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Philippines</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,284,1470]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Specimens examined. All 
<collectingCountry box="[631,751,1404,1430]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Philippine</collectingCountry>
and Afrotropical 
<typeStatus box="[973,1038,1404,1430]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">types</typeStatus>
, 
<typeStatus box="[1053,1156,1404,1430]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calvus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ommatius calvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
de Meijere, and 
<collectingCountry box="[537,658,1444,1470]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Philippine</collectingCountry>
species (see species list below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
